`crates/` is the workspace root: a family of independent CLI/library
crates implementing the ctx context-generation and verification system.
Depending on the workspace as a whole gets you the full pipeline —
scanning (`ctx-scan`), summarization (`ctx-summarize`), serving/hooking
(`ctx-context`), status tracking (`ctx-status`), brief generation
(`ctx-brief`), sandboxed execution (`ctx-cage`), verification
(`ctx-verify`), and shared primitives (`ctx-core`) — but each crate is
usable and versioned on its own; there is no umbrella API.

The crates share a small set of on-disk contracts rather than code:
the `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` mirror-path layout is written by `ctx-summarize`,
maintained/staled-checked by `ctx-scan`, and read/rendered by
`ctx-context`; `docs/status.json`/`docs/STATUS.md` is written and read by
`ctx-status` and also consumed by `ctx-brief`; `ctx-core` supplies the
denylist, hash-sidecar schema, and STATUS.md table codec that both
`ctx-scan` and `ctx-status` depend on to stay bit-compatible. A change to
any of these on-disk formats must be checked against every crate that
reads or writes it, since there's no shared library enforcing the
contract beyond `ctx-core`.

`ctx-cage` is the odd one out: it isolates *agent execution* itself
(filesystem/network sandboxing) rather than manipulating context
documents, and is a dependency of whichever crate spawns agent
subprocesses in production use, not of the document pipeline directly.

Every crate here independently follows the same pattern — a `src/`
implementation behind fake-based trait seams (`Fs`/`Agent`/`Env`/etc.)
and a `tests/` suite that pins the external contract via those fakes —
but each crate's fakes are private to it; there's no shared fake crate.

No `intent.md` exists at the workspace root, so no divergence check applies.